Pathophysiolgy

The pathophysiology of GBS involves an inflammatory response against either the myelin or the axon of peripheral nerves due to molecular mimicry and cross reactivity with the infectious antigen.

All myelinated nerves are involved : motor, sensory, autonomic and cranial
1. "This form of GBS is distinguished from AIDP by its selective involvement of motor nerves. Sensory nerves are not affected"
1. The most common presenting symptom of MFS is diplopia, which arises due to the acute onset of external ophthalmoplegia. Source
[!INFO] Demyelination vs. Axonal damage

  • In AIDP and Miller Fischer syndreom the inflammation targets the myelin producing Schwann cells. --> demyelination occurs. Lymphocytic infiltration present.
  • In AMAN and AMSAN, immune reactions occur against the axonal membrane. No lymphocytic infiltration.
    [!TIP] Mnemonic: If the name contains 'I', then myelin is involved and infiltration with lymphocytes occurs.

Aetiology of GBS

  • Preceding campylobacter infection - commonest
  • CMV infection
  • Influenza A and B infection
  • others

Time course of symptoms:

  • Patient notice a problem and present within 1 week.
  • Symptoms progress over the next few weeks and peaks at 4 weeks.
  • Subacute progression can take 4 - 8 weeks.
  • If symptom progression takes more than 8 weeks, the dianosis is chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (CIDP)<- UpToDate mentions a polyradiculoneuropathy.
  • Bowel and bladder dysfunction at onset makes GBS unlikely.

CIDP Vs. AIDP

CIDP AIDP
8 weeks to peak symptoms 4 weeks
progresses with intermittent relapses Monophasic
Patient retains the ability to walk independently
Lack of cranial neuropathy or respiratory involvement
Precise onset isn't easily identified (neither is the cause)
  • 80% regain the ability to walk independently.
  • 50% recover completely by one year. (and 50% do not)
  • but 10% have lasting severe motor impairment.
  • 1/5th die if they become ventilator dependent.
  • Poor prognostic factors
    • Age > 60
    • Preceding diarrhoeal illness
    • and some other obvious ones

Acute haemolytic transfusion reactions

Nonhaemolytic febrile reactions

Diagnosis of exclusion because the fever can be due to many things like infection of febrile transufion reaction.
Caused by cytokines from WBCs in the Red cell or platelet transfusion which cause fever / chills / rigors. Source

Circulatory overload

Volume overload causes pulmonary oedema.

Allergic reactions

  • IgE mediated (not by cytokines).
  • Allergens in this case are plasma or cell bound proteins from the donor.

TRALI

Tranfusion related acute lung injury
A type of febrile non-haemolytic transufion reaction - Medscape
Associated with mortality around 15% but much higher in critically ill patients.

  • 2 possible mechanisms:

    1. HLA class I or HLA class I antibodies from the donor react with lung neutrophils antigens in the recipient triggering inflammation.
    2. Some other bioactive substance in the donor blood / product cause activation of neutrophils already sequestered and primed (due to stressors like surgery or infection) in the recipient lungs.
    3. These two mechanisms may occur in sequence; i.e a two hit hypothesis whereby antibodies and other substances in the donor plasma activate already primed neutrophils.

  • Occurs due to leukocyte antibodies from the donor; most commonly in multiparous female donors - Kumar and Clark

  • Either way, the result is non cardiogenic pulmonary oedema.

  • The recipient develops acute onset cough, SOB and fever and perihilar and lower zone shadowing in the CXR shortly after transfusion (within 6 hours).

  • Treatment: Supportive with oxygen / ventilation with lung protective strategies. Steroids have no benefit.

  • Usually resolves in 2 to 4 days.

  • Can occur with FFP and platelets. Measures to reduce TRALI incidence are avoidance of using female plasma and testing female donors for leucocyte antibodies.

| low gamma globulin | recurrent enterocolitis and ? sinopulmonary infections | Giardia, enteroviruses, CMV, campylobacter |

Recurrent sinopulmonary infections and persistence of gut pathogens.
Leads to bronchiectasis and chronic diarrhoea with malabsorption.

[!INFO] Commonest significant antibody deficiency affecting children and adults.

Diagnosed at: 20 and 45 years of age.

? etiology - few are inherited. Pattern may by #autosomalDominant with low penetrance or #autosomal-Recessive - UpToDate

There is

  • B cells are present but they don't produce antibodies (i.e are ?nonfunctional?)
    • B cell numbers are normal but there are low levels of isotype switched B memory cells and plasma cells.
  • Low levels of all immunoglobulin classes
  • Frequent bacterial infections.

Lymphoma is a common cause of death in these patients.

Complications:

  • Recurrent infections - sinopulmonary (with encapsulated Streptococcus pneumoniae and Haemophilus influenzae and others) -> can lead to bronchiectasis.
  • Autoimmune disorders - RA, vitiligo, haemolytic anaemia.
  • Lymphoma

Chronic giadia infections with malabsorption can occur.

Agammaglobulinaemia

#2021BSQ-JUL Q24
Also called hypogammaglobulinaemia.

Mutation of the BTK gene impairs B cell maturation -> causes low or absent mature B cells -> severe hypogammaglobulinaemia.
Commonest inheritance: #x-linked-recessive with mothers being carriers. #autosomal-Recessive inheritance is seen in 50%.

Manifestation: recurrent sinopulmonary infections.(From 6 to 12 months of age, otitis media, sinusitis, bronchitis, and pneumonia).
Common pathogens: Encapsulated pyogenic bacteria Haemophillus influenzae and strep pneumoniae.

Treatment: repeaded IVIG transfusions or stem cell transplant.

  • SLE - ANA, Anti DsDNA, Anti Smith (Sm), Anti Ro, Anti La (Ro, La and Smith are named after patients)
